Task 1: Install and Configure binwalk
Subtask 1.1: Install binwalk and Dependencies
First, we need to install binwalk and its required dependencies on our Linux system.

# Update package repositories
sudo apt update

# Install binwalk and essential dependencies
sudo apt install -y binwalk python3-pip git

# Install additional extraction tools
sudo apt install -y mtd-utils gzip bzip2 tar arj lhasa p7zip p7zip-full cabextract cramfsprogs cramfsswap squashfs-tools sleuthkit default-jdk lzop srecord

# Install Python dependencies for advanced features
pip3 install python-magic pycrypto
Subtask 1.2: Verify Installation
Let's verify that binwalk is properly installed and check its version.

# Check binwalk version
binwalk --help

# Verify extraction capabilities
binwalk --list-plugins
Subtask 1.3: Download Sample Firmware
We'll download a sample firmware image for analysis. Create a working directory first.

# Create working directory
mkdir ~/firmware_lab
cd ~/firmware_lab

# Download sample firmware (using a publicly available router firmware)
wget https://downloads.openwrt.org/releases/22.03.0/targets/ath79/generic/openwrt-22.03.0-ath79-generic-tplink_archer-c7-v2-squashfs-sysupgrade.bin

# Alternatively, create a sample firmware for demonstration
dd if=/dev/zero of=sample_firmware.bin bs=1024 count=1024
